<div id="review_3381816302" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3381816302" />
    <a title="Annie Ryan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9348974-annie-ryan"><img alt="Annie Ryan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1508688731p2/9348974.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3381816302?book_show_action=true">Jun 21, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Annie Ryan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Annie Ryan" href="/user/show/9348974-annie-ryan">Annie Ryan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3381816302" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13174048298615490961">This is the powerful story of two boys, Lafeyette and Pharoah, their mom, LaJoe, and their other family and friends who lived in the Henry Horner Homes, just one of the many housing projects in Chicago back in the late 1980’s. Even though this book was published in 1991, it is still a MUST-READ, because it brings the reader perspective on what it’s like to be poor and black as a child in America. I can not imagine having the childhood that these children had: the financial struggles their famili</span>
  <span id="freeText13174048298615490961" style="display:none">This is the powerful story of two boys, Lafeyette and Pharoah, their mom, LaJoe, and their other family and friends who lived in the Henry Horner Homes, just one of the many housing projects in Chicago back in the late 1980’s. Even though this book was published in 1991, it is still a MUST-READ, because it brings the reader perspective on what it’s like to be poor and black as a child in America. I can not imagine having the childhood that these children had: the financial struggles their families faced, the fear of violence they felt everywhere they went (but especially in their own homes), the way they felt “tired” from their daily lives and the longing they felt to get out of the projects, and the uncertainty about their future (“If I grow up, instead of when I grow up...”). The title really had an impact on me. As LaJoe states when talking with the author about his idea for a book about the children at Henry Horner, “But you know there are no children here. They’ve seen too much to be children.” This non-fiction book is heart-breaking, but I’m so glad I was introduced to these two brothers. Their stories will stick with me and I will always be rooting for them (just like I was at Pharoah’s school spelling bee!). </span>
  <a data-text-id="13174048298615490961" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


