<div id="review_2844318113" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2844318113" />
    <a title="Emily Jameson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16282009-emily-jameson"><img alt="Emily Jameson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1357780411p2/16282009.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2844318113?book_show_action=true">Jun 11, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emily Jameson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emily Jameson" href="/user/show/16282009-emily-jameson">Emily Jameson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2844318113" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13928984279340313963">Alex Kotlowitz wrote this book after spending time with a family living in the Henry Horner Housing Projects, in the midst of peak levels of gang and drug related crime among its residents. The Henry Horner homes have since been demolished, and the area is going through a gentrification process that is lowering the crime rates in the area. This book, at almost 30 years old, provides a harrowing historical look into life for predominantly poor, black, single parent families. <br/><br/>As a reader, I couldn</span>
  <span id="freeText13928984279340313963" style="display:none">Alex Kotlowitz wrote this book after spending time with a family living in the Henry Horner Housing Projects, in the midst of peak levels of gang and drug related crime among its residents. The Henry Horner homes have since been demolished, and the area is going through a gentrification process that is lowering the crime rates in the area. This book, at almost 30 years old, provides a harrowing historical look into life for predominantly poor, black, single parent families. <br /><br />As a reader, I couldn’t help rooting for the Rivers family to overcome their horrible circumstances. However, their environment and challenges didn’t allow much for a better way of life. With every step forward, a multitude of obstacles pushed them back.<br /><br />This book should be a “must” read as a historical look at urban America and housing projects, as well as a sociological examination of poverty and race. This book sent me on a frantic internet search for more information on housing projects, gang involvement in the late 80s, and the outcome of the Rivers family 30 years later. This was an extremely provocative book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13928984279340313963" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


