<div id="review_2990575689" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2990575689" />
    <a title="Brigette" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6152862-brigette"><img alt="Brigette" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1631069533p2/6152862.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2990575689?book_show_action=true">Oct 01, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brigette" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brigette" href="/user/show/6152862-brigette">Brigette</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2990575689&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2990575689" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11187735861683435022">Once again I will say, how can you rate someone else’s life story? I disliked LaJoe at times and at the same time felt pity for her as a mother. I was sad for Pharoah, but glad things eventually worked out for him. I am not surprised that Dawn came to have 5 children, or that LaJoe had 8. What is surprising to me is that they had so many children knowing that most of their futures were bleak. If I knew that my offspring’s future was already doomed, I could not and would not have children, but th</span>
  <span id="freeText11187735861683435022" style="display:none">Once again I will say, how can you rate someone else’s life story? I disliked LaJoe at times and at the same time felt pity for her as a mother. I was sad for Pharoah, but glad things eventually worked out for him. I am not surprised that Dawn came to have 5 children, or that LaJoe had 8. What is surprising to me is that they had so many children knowing that most of their futures were bleak. If I knew that my offspring’s future was already doomed, I could not and would not have children, but that is me. I also felt LaJoe put many unnecessary expectations on Lafayette, an example would be her speaking with him about adult issues. Situations come at all of us from 2 directions, one is fate and the other is choice. I can’t say, from what I read here, if all the problems the Rivers family faced were fate driven, however the book tends to lean towards that being the case. I believe a lot of what transpired was because of choices they made, and some of the things they chose were tragic. The story itself was engrossing, and caught my attention within the first chapter. I wanted to know more about all their lives. The description of the characters, though mostly not comparable to myself, I felt were tangible. It’s interesting to me that a book about 2 boys in Chicago would read more like a story about a mother and her issues with her kids. I wish the best outcomes for all the Rivers family. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11187735861683435022" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


